<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.space.com/news/unispace2.html">A Protest at Unispace III: No Guns, Nukes in Space</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
http://www.space.com/news/unispace2.html<br>
By George T. Whitesides<br>
Special to space.com 21 July 1999<br>
<br>
VIENNA -- Protests against the militarization and 'nuclearization' of space shook up the Third United Nations Conference on the Exploration and Peaceful Uses of Outer Space today. Delegates to the conference - otherwise known as UNISPACE III - were confronted both inside and outside the sleek concrete walls of the Austrian International Center as official opening speeches gently echoed harsher words distributed outside. <br>
<br>
&quot;There is urgent need for the demilitarization of outer space and a reduction in military-related activities,&quot; stated Y.M. Tiwari of India, the official conference spokesman for 77 developing countries and China. &quot;[We are] also concerned with the increased use of radio-isotopes for power generation in space objects.&quot; <br>
<br>
This later objection, concerned centrally with the accidental re-entry or explosive distribution of radioactive elements from space systems, could also be heard along the entryway to the conference. There, representatives of the Global Network Against Weapons and Nuclear Power in Space pressed photocopies and pamphlets into the outstretched hands of curious delegates. <br>
<br>
&quot;Ban space weapons and space-based military installations by national and international law,&quot; read the organization's July pamphlet. Alleging that an accident could &quot;pollute the Earth atmosphere and cause thousands of deaths,&quot; the slightly bedraggled activists also called on the U.N. to &quot;ban the use of nuclear power in space.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Nuclear energy [in space] has been subject to a lot of irrational fear,&quot; responded Dr. Franklin Chang-Diaz, a veteran U.S. astronaut who made several presentations today. &quot;Folks have to make it clear in their minds what the choices really are.&quot; Arguing that nuclear power in space could be made adequately safe and that space exploration required abundant energy, Chang-Diaz noted starkly that, &quot;in space, power is life. We must have a power-rich environment.&quot; <br>
<br>
With the U.S. military preparing to dominate space via new spy satellites, laser-based anti-satellite weapons, and even considerations of a space plane, official calls for the peaceful use of space took on added urgency. &quot;Above all, we must guard against the misuse of outer space,&quot; said Kofi Annan, U.N. Secretary General, in his opening speech. &quot;We cannot view the expanse of space as another battleground for our earthly conflicts.&quot; <br>
<br>
Whether these protests will have any effect remains to be seen. But the warnings underscore the changing nature of space, as space-faring nations reach to gain both new scientific knowledge and the military upper hand.<br>
<br>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<br>
 (mixing threads dreadfully) In keeping with that <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showMessage?topicID=94.topic">letter</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.space4peace.org/">GNAWaNPiS</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> and forging conversational links with them (BTW, we've linked to them frequently -sometimes even in fair terms- How many times have they acknowledged us?), I point out that we do feel that they're in the right, as far as urging the peaceful uses of space. We just don't at all agree that nuclear doesn't have a place up there -quite the contrary, nuclear frequently is not just a power source of choice, it's the only reasonable choice.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;Chang-Diaz noted starkly that, &quot;in space, power is life.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
 <br>
 He might also say that radiation and deadly conditions are the natural environment in space. Other than harming humankind's access to space, future activities in space, or the Earth, there's no reason to outright ban any &amp; all nuclear energy in space -up to and including nuclear pulse rockets. Everything else -like their fears of RTG safety and general weaponization- is covered by treaties. They don't need to pay special attention to RTGs inherently, just irresponsible use of them.<br>
<br>
 &lt;Chuckles&gt; BTW, Have to wonder what they think of the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://fourmilab.to/documents/spaceguns/">Russian guns in space</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->... Fat chance of convincing them to drop the guns in the Soyuz survival kits to face wolves barehanded...<br>
<br>
Also, as a gesture of goodwill, should we inform them of our substantial interest in, and the even more substantial literature about Orion? They don't have a word about it. (Not sure if I should indicate humor here... Either it's a good idea, or I'll be scalped!) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1518<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/18/02 1:38:17 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=273.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.gothicbarbie.net/images/electric.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/spaceh.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nukes in Space.</span><hr size=1> Funny you should notice that link aswell. I liked the comment from an Astronaut that &quot;..in Space, power is life..&quot; so I used it as the header of a thread over in the Nuclear Spacecraft category with the article sourced.<br>
<br>
I think opinion on military use of atomic power in space varies. You obviously oppose it. I myself do not see any way in which atomic weapons can ever be abolished. Their use in Space seems only natural. In previous posts at other boards you have highlighted the danger of kinetic weapons and the only way of defending against such superweapons would be a space military. To try and deprive such a force of nuclear arsenals would be self defeating. A military without such weapons would be defenceless against any enemy with them. In space there will be no considerations about contaminating territory. In a space war whoever has atomics wins. Its as simple as that. Plus, they might prove useful in deflecting a kinetic weapon when all else fails.<br>
<br>
This would make a good thread. &quot;Should Space be militarised?&quot; <p>
